<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / International Company News: Mannesmann chief fires final
salvo at critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUSSELDORF
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Anxious shareholders yesterday heard Mr Werner Dieter refute what he called
'grotesque' charges that he had lined his own pockets while chief executive
of Mannesmann, one of Germany's largest companies.
Speaking to the annual meeting for the last time before his planned
resignation, Mr Dieter insisted he would not allow himself to become the
victim of a press smear campaign.
He told shareholders he had received an anonymous letter in November warning
him that a campaign would be launched against any attempts to become
chairman of the supervisory board, the non-executive board which oversees
management.
The Dusseldorf state prosecutor began an investigation last week into
allegations in Der Spiegel, he weekly news magazine, that Mr Dieter forced
Rexroth, a Mannesmann subsidiary, to buy products at inflated prices from
Hydac, a company largely owned by Mr Dieter's family.
The allegations have attracted prominent press coverage, coming on the heels
of a variety of other scandals this year. In an unusual move, police were
called to be on hand at yesterday's meeting because of Mannesmann management
fears that left-wing extremists would try to interrupt proceedings. As it
happened, their presence was unnecessary.
Mr Dieter, 64, has been chief executive of the group since 1985. He will be
succeeded by Mr Joachim Funk, the finance director. Although Mr Dieter goes
on to become an ordinary member of the supervisory board, he said he would
seek the board chairmanship once external auditors had presented their
report into the allegations.
Turnover for the year was expected to reach DM30bn (Dollars 19.1bn), up from
DM27.96bn in 1993 when the group lost DM513m. Turnover in the first six
months was up 10 per cent to DM14.3bn, exceeding analysts' expectations.
Orders in the same period totalled DM16.8bn, 19 per cent higher than a year
ago.
The group's D2 mobile telephone network, one of two in Germany and the
group's fastest growing unit, now had 700,000 customers, up from 580,000 at
the end of May, the meeting heard.
The links between Rexroth, an engineering company, and Hydac, which makes
magnets and hydraulics accessories, 'were interesting for both companies',
Mr Dieter said.
Mr Dieter had held a 30 per cent stake in Rexroth, but sold this when he
moved to Mannesmann. This, he said, was proof that he had sought to avoid a
conflict of interest.
However, several small shareholders said any suggestion that Mr Dieter might
have benefited from his position as chief executive should rule him out of a
position on the supervisory board.
</TEXT>
