<DATE>940709
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / UK Company News: AromaScan valued at Pounds 35m in main
market flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AromaScan, the developers of an 'electronic nose' - a new technology to
detect odours - yesterday announced plans for a stock market flotation
valuing the group at between Pounds 35m and Pounds 40m.
The float is expected to raise Pounds 12m, of which Pounds 4m will be set
aside for working capital and Pounds 8m used to build a manufacturing plant
and develop technology which, according to the company, has applications for
industries ranging from food and drink to cosmetics.
Mr Allan Syms, managing director, said it was a big breakthrough. 'We have
developed the first machine capable of producing the digital fingerprint of
a smell,' he stated.
Unlike rival technologies, AromaScan's electronic nose relies on a large
library of polymers to identify smells and produce digital print-outs. It
can, for example, spot the difference between genuine and fake Chanel
perfume or detect contamination in recycled bottles.
That technology was pioneered and developed at the University of Manchester
Institute of Science and Technology (Umist) and has been used by the US Food
and Drug Administration and companies such as Whitbread and Unilever.
Mr Syms estimated the potential worldwide market at Pounds 215m, although he
warned that development costs were likely to lead to losses of Pounds 1.91m
next year and Pounds 863,000 in 1996.
The pathfinder prospectus, however, showed the group making profits of
Pounds 4.02m in 1997 on projected turnover of Pounds 18.4m.
Under the terms of the flotation - handled through a placing by NM
Rothschild with Peel Hunt acting as broker - existing shareholders have
agreed to retain their stakes for at least two years.
They include AromaScan management, which currently holds 30 per cent; Umist
with 10 per cent and 70 private investors holding the balance.
Mr Fred Worth, finance and operations director, said funds raised by the
placing would also be used to repay a Pounds 500,000 loan to Umist, while
Legal and General - one of the original backers - would receive Pounds
300,000 from existing cash balances.
Impact day is July 26 and dealings are expected to begin on August 3.
</TEXT>
