</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / G7 Summit in Naples: US welcomes tax plans by Japanese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAPLES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US officials yesterday welcomed what they saw as a new commitment by the
Japanese government to stimulate dom-estic demand through an income tax cut
and so open new market opportunities for other countries.
Although Japan has already cut income tax and plans another cut of the same
size next year, it had intended to offset this cut with a consumption tax,
thereby eliminating the effect on domestic demand.
But US officials said Mr Tomiichi Murayama, Japan's new prime minister,
assured President Bill Clinton at a meeting in Naples that his coalition
would not go ahead with the consumption tax until the Japanese economy had
started to grow again.
The bilateral meeting preceded the formal summit of heads of government from
the Group of Seven leading industrial nations, which began in Naples last
night.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US Treasury secretary, said Mr Masayoshi Takemura, his
Japanese opposite number, had assured him he 'would not detract from the
income tax cut until they were sure that they were well on the way to
recovery'.
Mr Clinton also said that Japan had not made enough progress towards opening
up its markets to foreign goods, and that he looked forward to a quick
resumption of the US-Japan framework trade negotiations. Nevertheless, he
showed much greater understanding than in the past for the political
difficulties faced by the Japanese government in opening up its markets.
Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, said he would also be pressing the
Japanese government for trade liberalisation measures at the summit.
Mr Clinton plans to broach to his colleagues an idea for further action to
follow up on the free trade promises they made in the Uruguay Round of
negotiations. Besides urging the other G7 countries to ratify the Uruguay
Round agreement, he said he would ask them to review and analyse remaining
trade barriers and report back to next year's summit in Halifax, Canada.
In a letter to the other G7 leaders, Mr Clinton mentioned financial
services, standards and investment rules as examples of areas that largely
escaped scrutiny in the Uruguay Round.
A senior US official said this initiative, dubbed Open Markets 2000, was
intended to maintain the momentum towards freer trade. Nevertheless,
ratification of the Uruguay Round agreement remained the US's first priority
and Open Markets 2000 was not intended to open a new 'Clinton Round' of
talks.
The idea was welcomed by Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian premier, who
agreed on the need for 'more incisive measures', particularly in the area of
financial services.
</TEXT>
