<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / Germany cuts conscription
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German government yesterday decided that conscripts in the German armed
forces will have to serve 10 months instead of 12, part of a package of
reforms designed to trim the Bundeswehr from 370,000 to 340,000. A total of
DM47.5bn (Pounds 19.6bn) will be earmarked for the 1995 military budget. The
new structure of the Bundeswehr will have 290,000 troops assigned to the
so-called main defence forces and a further 50,000 in crisis reaction forces
where soldiers must serve at least 12 months.
The crisis reaction troops could see action as part of United Nations
operations, a thorny issue which the German constitutional court is expected
to decide next Tuesday, when it will rule whether German troops can be
deployed outside the Nato area.
</TEXT>
