<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / Two-tier system for rand 'likely to go'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN and MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Africa's cumbersome two-tier exchange rate system was 'fundamentally
wrong' and its abolition only a matter of time, Mr Chris Liebenberg, the
country's finance minister-designate, said yesterday.
However, any decision to abolish the two-tier system had to be 'taken
against a background of sound, sustainable government', Mr Liebenberg said,
and would depend on the country's reserves and on international confidence.
He acknowledged that his appointment this week as replacement to Mr Derek
Keys could have been better handled but said he had received a personal
reassurance from President Nelson Mandela that the government had a
commitment to fiscal discipline.
Mr Liebenberg, 60, was appointed on Tuesday, hours after Mr Keys shocked
financial markets with his unexpected announcement that he planned to step
down this year for personal reasons.
In an interview, Mr Liebenberg, formerly head of banking group Nedcor, said
he fully supported the reconstruction and development programme, the
centrepiece of government economic policy.
The programme's success was 'absolutely essential' but this could be
achieved within current spending limits.
'Implied in that (the RDP's success) is very strict fiscal discipline that
brings with it very strict monetary discipline,' he said. Mr Liebenberg, who
said he had no formal political affiliation, accepted that Tuesday's news,
which had been preceded by rumours of Mr Keys' resignation, had done damage
as government bond rates rose half a point, and the currency weakened.
'There is no doubt there is a Keys factor but that a correction in the
market was going to take place was inevitable,' he said. But Mr Liebenberg
acknowledged that 'with hindsight, had everything been perfect, it could
have been better handled.'
On the question of the abolition of exchange controls, Mr Liebenberg said he
was no supporter of the current system. 'I believe that South Africa's
two-tier exchange rate is fundamentally, inherently wrong. It cannot last.
This principle is accepted. It is now a matter of timing.'
Three issues would affect the decision to abolish the financial rand: the
level of reserves, the overhang of speculative financial rands in the
banking system, and international confidence.
</TEXT>
