<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / International Company News: Gantry drops out of Bridge Oil
race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The hard-fought bid battle for Bridge Oil, the Sydney-based oil and gas
group, appeared to be over last night, after Gantry, one of the two rival
suitors, dropped out of the race.
Gantry - which was the bid vehicle for Enron, the US natural gas company,
and the California Public Employees Retirement System, one of the largest
state pension funds - said it would not proceed with an offer. This leaves
the way clear for Parker &amp; Parsley, the Texan oil independent, to go ahead
with its 90-cents-a-share cash bid.
Gantry said P&amp;P's public statement that it would not accept a
95-cents-a-share offer for its 21 per cent holding in Bridge, meant that
Gantry had no hope of reaching its 90 per cent minimum acceptance level.
'Thus, we have decided not to proceed with this transaction,' it said.
Gantry had bought Bridge shares in the market on Thursday at prices up to 95
cents, boosting the target company's share price. However, during
yesterday's trading, Bridge shares eased to 91 cents. Gantry's announcement
came after the market closed.
Santos, the South Australian oil and gas company, is buying a 32.802 per
cent interest in the Anglia gas field in the North Sea from Conoco, the oil
and gas subsidiary of Dupont in the US.
Santos said the deal, which is still subject to regulatory and joint venture
approval, had been under negotiation for some time, and would be backdated
to January 1, 1994. The company declined to disclose its price 'due to
confidentiality provisions'.
The deal will boost Santos' budgeted gas production this calendar year by
5.3 per cent, and add 1.15m barrels of oil equivalent to the group's 1994
production. Proven gas reserves at the purchase date were put at more than
50bn cubic feet.
Santos said its share of gas production from the Anglia field, which started
producing in late-1991, had been sold forward under a 'life of field'
contract to Total Gas Marketing. The other joint venture partners in Anglia
are Ranger Oil and Amerada Hess.
Although this is Santos' first investment in the North Sea, the company said
it would consider further acquisitions there.
