<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / International Company News: Outokumpu FM1.4bn issue goes
ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Outokumpu, the Finnish mining and metals group, yesterday went ahead with a
FM1.4bn (Dollars 270m) share issue, following Nokia, the tele-communications
company which this week completed a FM2.5bn issue, the biggest international
offering by a Finnish company.
Outokumpu fixed the price for the offered units of one A share and one
warrant at FM82.50.
The company is issuing 13.5m units, while the Finnish state, until now the
majority shareholder, is selling 4.5m. Subscribers have the right to trade
six warrants for one A share at a price of FM92 before June 28 1996.
The pricing compared with a closing price for Outokumpu A shares of FM83 on
Wednes-day.
Outokumpu said a further 3.3m units had been granted to the underwriters as
an over-allotment option. If these are taken up, the issue will raise a
total of FM1.3bn for Outokumpu and FM480m for the state.
Strong demand from both overseas and Finnish investors will have come as a
relief to Outokumpu, as there had been some nervousness that the weakness of
worldwide stock markets and a heavy flow of issues from Finland in recent
months would dampen enthusiasm.
The proceeds are to be used to strengthen Outokumpu's balance sheet and to
reduce debt.
If the over-allotment option is fully taken up, the state's holding in
Outokumpu, which strengthened profits strongly in the first four months,
will fall from 50.1 per cent to 38.2 per cent, the latest in a series of
similar moves to reduce state ownership in Finnish industry.
The Outokumpu issue followed a successful issue by Nokia, the star of the
Finnish stock exchange which last week became the first Finnish company to
be listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
Nokia's original offer of 5m shares was eventually raised to 6m, raising a
total of FM2.5bn to help fund its fast-growing mobile telephones business.
