<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / UK Company News: P&amp;P adds QA to its training operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
P&amp;P is consolidating its move away from computer distribution with the
acquisition of QA Training, one of the UK's leading computer training
companies, for up to Pounds 18m. The purchase will be funded partly by a
1-for-4 rights issue at 60p to raise Pounds 8.6m.
P&amp;P also released its interim figures, which showed continued recovery
following its exit from volume computer distribution last year.
Pre-tax profits rose 35 per cent from Pounds 2m to Pounds 2.7m in the six
months to end-May on turnover from continuing operations up 27 per cent from
Pounds 93.8m to Pounds 119m.
Earnings per share increased from 2.1p to 3p and the interim dividend is
raised from 0.8p to 0.95p.
Mr David Southworth, group managing director, said the company was seeing
good growth across the board, which would be enhanced by the acquisition of
QA. 'It will expand P&amp;P's skill base and corporate client base, and provides
us with enhanced opportunities for the future.'
QA is the UK market leader, with an estimated 20 per cent share, in the
provision of technical training in desktop computing. It trains staff within
companies who develop and support computer systems. It made an operating
profit of Pounds 1.78m last year on turnover of Pounds 9.37m.
Mr Southworth said it would complement P&amp;P's existing training operation,
which has turnover of about Pounds 3m a year.
The vendors of QA - comprising its top management, its employees, and IBM,
which has a 10 per cent stake - will receive an initial Pounds 15m in cash,
shares and loan notes. There will be an additional payment of up to Pounds
3m, equal to six times the amount by which QA's profits exceed Pounds 2m in
the year to April 1995.
Phoenix Securities advised P&amp;P on the deal and the rights issue has been
fully underwritten by Panmure Gordon.
</TEXT>
