<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / UK Company News: British Bloodstock moves out of the red
with Pounds 124,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After three years of losses, British Bloodstock Agency returned to the black
in the 12 months to March 31 with a pre-tax profit of Pounds 124,000.
Shares in the USM-traded company, however, fell 13p to 92p yesterday, as the
result fell short of some market estimates of between Pounds 250,000 and
Pounds 300,000.
Mr Christo Philipson, chairman, pointed out that the result, which compared
with a Pounds 38,000 loss previously, continued the steady improvement in
trading results which began in the second half of 1991.
He attributed the recovery to a substantial reduction in fixed costs and the
first increase in turnover since 1990 - up 4 per cent at Pounds 5.22m.
Despite the return to profits, no dividend is recommended. Mr Philipson
explained that he believed reserves should be strengthened following the
lossmaking years and that the improvement in fortunes must be sustained
before payments could be recommenced.
Earnings per share were 2.7p (1.4p losses).
The chairman said greater industry confidence reflected the beneficial
change in VAT legislation in the spring 1993 Budget and an increase in prize
money.
He expected the market to benefit from further increases in prize money,
funded by the evening opening of betting shops and Sunday racing, and also
in breeders' prizes, which are set to top the Pounds 1m mark in 1995.
Mr Peter Bickmore, managing director, has decided to step down in order to
concentrate on running BBA Insurance Services and expanding the group's
insurance interests. He will however, remain an executive director.
</TEXT>
