<DATE>940708
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / UK Company News: Greene King static at Pounds 20.4m -
Government asked to cut beer duty to combat cheap imports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Greene King, the regional brewer, yesterday blamed the lingering recession
in East Anglia for a flat performance during the 12 months to May 1 with
underlying pre-tax profits rising just 1 per cent to Pounds 20.4m.
The Suffolk-based company said it had endured one of the longest and deepest
recessions in memory, and beer volumes in its home market had fallen 7 per
cent.
However, Mr Simon Redman, chairman, said the brewer had managed to restrict
its own sales decline to 0.6 per cent and contributions from newly-acquired
pubs in other areas helped group turnover increase 5 per cent to Pounds
146.1m (Pounds 139m).
He claimed this was a creditable result in a fragile market where many
breweries were suffering from cheap European beer imports.
Calling on the government to help the UK industry by reducing beer duty
rates from 30p a pint to less than 10p, he warned: 'Failure to act merely
exports jobs and passes tax revenue to our European neighbours.'
Difficult trading conditions and the impact of continental imports meant
prospects remained patchy, he added, even though pre-tax profits rose 18 per
cent on an FRS 3 basis.
The figures were distorted by exceptional costs of Pounds 2.8m arising from
the abortive 1993 bid for Morland, the Thames Valley-based brewer.
Trading profits were held at Pounds 26.7m (Pounds 26.8m) as the group
struggled with its brewing and wholesaling business, where profits fell
sharply from Pounds 9.1m to Pounds 6.9m.
The shortfall was offset by slightly improved profits in the tenanted trade
 -which overcame intense price competition and discounting to report profits
of Pounds 15.2m (Pounds 14.8m) - and a 24 per cent upturn in profits in the
retail trade to Pounds 10.5m (Pounds 8.5m).
The acquisition of 44 pubs from Bass helped the managed pubs division
improve margins with drink sales growing 12 per cent and food sales
increasing 49 per cent.
The Pounds 17.5m Bass acquisition took capital spending to Pounds 37.6m,
while gearing rose from 34 per cent to 39 per cent.
Adjusted earnings per share came out at 35.9p (35.6p) and a final dividend
of 9.05p is proposed, making 12.9p (12.3p) for the year.
COMMENT
Although the results were slightly below expectations, Greene King should
emerge from its local difficulties in a stronger position. It has shifted
its bias away from tenanted pubs, where price cutting has been fiercest, to
develop its managed estate while also building a reputation outside East
Anglia. That effort will be boosted shortly by the opening of its Camberley
depot to serve southern England and restoring its in-house canning
operations. These developments are expected to lift profits this year to
Pounds 22.5m, putting the shares on a prospective multiple of 12 - below the
market sector's average.
</TEXT>
