<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Schroders builds up Wall Street presence: Chairman sees
further US investment as merchant bank pays Dollars 92m for Wertheim control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Schroders yesterday announced a deal giving it one of the largest presences
on Wall Street of a UK merchant bank. The Dollars 92m (Pounds 60.5m)
purchase for the half of US-based investment bank Wertheim Schroders it does
not already control would allow Schroders to make further investment in a US
arm, according to Mr George Mallinckrodt, Schroders chairman.
Schroders already has a presence in the US through its asset management arm,
which was the largest non-US manager of international investments as of
March 31, 1994, according to the trade publication Pensions and Investments.
Of the Pounds 6.5bn in net new cash it attracted last year, nearly Pounds
4bn was from accounts outside the UK, with much coming from the US. The
increasing interest among US investors for non-US securities was a key
factor in Wertheim's decision to sell full control of the firm to Schroders,
Mr Mallinckrodt said. 'Two or three years ago, this was not really a factor.
That's what persuaded them to sell now,' he explained. 'In the future we can
target ourselves to introduce more foreign securities into the US.'
To this end, Mr Mallinckrodt said, Schroders hoped to expand Wertheim's
securities distribution capabilities in the US, as well as its corporate
base.
The acquisition of total control of Wertheim allows Schroders to draw the
firm into areas its management might have been reluctant to participate in,
such as expansion of its derivatives activities.
Mr Mallinckrodt said that Schroders might seek to raise Wertheim's capital
base to Dollars 250m from Dollars 177m in the next five years or so.
Schroders has owned 42.5 per cent of Wertheim's equity since 1986, a stake
which carries 50 per cent of the voting rights. Yesterday's deal will pay
Dollars 68m for the shares held by Wertheim's management and a further
Dollars 24m for the 15 per cent non-voting interest held by institutional
shareholders.
The acquisition price, which includes the assumption of some Dollars 65m in
Wertheim debt securities, values the company at about Dollars 310m. Wertheim
had net tangible assets of Dollars 179m at May 31, 1994, and for the year
ended December 31, 1993, pre-tax profits after exceptional items of Dollars
35m.
Wertheim last year paid roughly Dollars 20m to cover compensation and legal
fees to Ames, the US department store chain, over advice Ames received when
it made the Dollars 1.3bn purchase of the discount store division of Zayre
in 1988.
According to Securities Data in New York, Wertheim ranks 15th among
worldwide M&amp;A advisers so far this year, having worked on completed
transactions valued at Dollars 5.56bn. In 1993 the firm ranked 10th,
advising on Dollars 16.8bn in deals. However, in league tables showing
number of M&amp;A deals worked on, Wertheim stands higher - 12th in the
year-to-date, and 4th in 1993 - an indication that its corporate clients are
smaller in size than those advised by Wall Street's biggest banks such as
Goldman Sachs, Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley.
Mr James Harmon, Wertheim's chief executive, said it was wrong to label the
firm as serving the medium-sized corporate market, as it had particular
strengths in sectors such as chemicals.
The buy-out of Wertheim comes a time when other UK firms have been actively
developing US operations, with mixed success. Lazard has long had a presence
in US investment banking through its relationship with Lazard Freres, while
SG Warburg and NatWest Securities have begun to establish themselves in
various corners of the domestic securities markets. In contrast, Barclays de
Zoete Wedd has been unsuccessful in its attempt to build a US stock
brokerage business, while the 1991 partial merger between Baring Brothers
and Dillon Read has yet to pay significant dividends.
Mr Philip Gibbs, merchant banking analyst at BZW, said the deal offered
benefits for Schroders, even though, at 1.7 times net worth, it had paid a
premium over the going rate for US merchant banks. 'The fact that they have
worked together as partners for eight years augers well.'
If there is a disadvantage, it may be that the senior management of Wertheim
no longer has the incentive of sharing the profits as owners.
Wall Street's top earners receive compensation packages in the millions of
dollars, whereas London pay rates are much lower. Mr Harmon said talk of
tension over pay levels was off-target. 'We are well aware of this matter.
Clearly, you have to pay competitively, and we will continue to pay
competitively.' A Schroders banker in London said: 'The reality is that New
York pays more, and you have to pay local market rates.'
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
