<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Regulator regrets impact of job on husband's firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By:BY ROBERT CORZINE and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An architectural firm run by the husband of Ms Clare Spottiswoode, the gas
industry regulator, has decided to decline a Pounds 1m contract with British
Gas because of a potential conflict of interest.
Ms Spottiswoode yesterday expressed frustration that her public role could
have such a severe financial impact on people outside her family. She said
ORMS - the firm run by Mr Oliver Richards, her husband - might now have to
make some employees redundant. 'We did absolutely nothing improper or
illegal,' Mr Richards said yesterday. 'It's a problem of public perception
and what the press would do with it.'
ORMS was invited last May by British Gas to bid for the modernisation of an
office complex near Newcastle upon Tyne. It was the third time the firm had
dealt with British Gas's property division, which said it was unaware until
last Thursday that Mr Richards was Ms Spottiswoode's husband.
The first British Gas contract with ORMS was awarded early last year -
before Ms Spottiswoode was appointed director-general of Ofgas. It was a
small contract for a feasibility study in Swindon. The second, another small
contract for work in Poole, was awarded last November, days after Ms
Spottiswoode joined Ofgas.
She said she had immediately informed the Department of Trade and Industry,
which did not object to ORMS dealing with British Gas as long as her husband
was not directly involved and the amounts were not significant.
Last May, however, British Gas asked the company to bid for what turned out
to be a much larger contract. Ms Spottiswoode said the DTI again advised
that there was no legal objection. But it suggested she exercise her own
judgment, even though she had no direct influence on ORMS.
Mr Richards said he and his two other partners looked at ways to ensure that
he did not benefit from the contract, including the possibility of giving
his share of the profits to charity. But accountants advised them that there
was no practical way of doing so, and they decided to withdraw.
Mr Philip Kirby, the British Gas executive who dealt with ORMS, said the
firm was 'a good architectural practice which won the work fairly'. But he
said he wished it had told him of Mr Richards' connection to Ofgas.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>ORMS.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8712 Architectural Services.
</IN>
