<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Banham offers one rule for Essex and another for Dorset
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Southend and Basildon are to become free-standing local authorities, but the
rest of Essex will retain a two-tier system under proposals from the Local
Government Commission for England inadvertently sent to homes in the area
yesterday.
The leak, a week early, confirmed the commission's intention to leave the
two-tier status quo intact in most of England outside the main cities, in
spite of government requests that it recommend unitary authorities in all
but 'exceptional' circumstances.
Under the plans Thurrock would merge with Basildon New Town to form a
unitary authority while Southend would be given independence on its existing
boundaries. The county and 11 district councils would continue to provide
local government services in the rest of the county.
As an alternative, the commission suggests that the county council be
abolished and split into six unitaries. But this would involve merging
Colchester and Tendring districts, which have announced that they cannot
work together.
Under this option, the other unitary councils would be Braintree and
Uttlesford; Harlow, Epping Forest, Brentwood and Billericay; Thurrock and
Basildon New Town; Chelmsford and Maldon; and Southend-on-Sea, Castle Point
and Rochford.
Essex County Council welcomed the commission's preferred option, while the
Association of District Councils was unwilling to comment.
The Essex leak overshadowed the commission's formal announcement of plans
for Dorset, which would see Poole split from Bournemouth/Christchurch, with
both becoming unitary all-purpose authorities.
The rest of Dorset - including the present district councils of North
Dorset, East Dorset, Purbeck, West Dorset and Weymouth and Portland - would
be merged into a unitary authority. The county council would cease to exist.
This contrasts with the plans for Essex, and for neighbouring Hampshire,
where the commission recommended retaining the two-tier system outside the
bigger towns.
The plan to split Bournemouth, Poole and Christchurch angered the business
community, which had argued strongly for one new authority to cover the
conurbation.
The managing director of one of Bournemouth's largest employers said:
'Christchurch, Bournemouth and Poole look like one conurbation from the air
and they feel like one when you drive through them. Services I need come
from those three areas and they need co-ordination.'
Start-up costs of the plan would be between Pounds 20m and Pounds 22m,
according to the commission, generating annual savings of between Pounds 4m
and Pounds 7m. The commission is offering an alternative which would create
four unitary authorities for Dorset by splitting rural Dorset into two
councils.
</TEXT>
