<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Pergau dam row forces spending protocol change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has made an important concession in the wake of the Pergau
dam scandal by ruling that an independent accountancy watchdog must be
informed of any disagreement between a cabinet minister and permanent
secretary over expenditure plans.
The ruling, which was revealed in an official document prepared by Mr
Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, follows a disagreement
between officials at the Foreign Office in 1991 over whether Britain should
contribute to the Pergau project.
Mr Dorrell's decision will mean that any minister officially overruling a
top civil servant on expenditure matters will have to inform Sir John Bourn,
the comptroller and auditor-general.
This will in effect mean that such a disagreement could quickly be debated
by MPs on the Commons' public accounts committee, which first asked the
government to examine procedures in such cases.
The change to procedure, which came to light in recently published Treasury
minutes, follows a disagreement at the Foreign Office in February 1991 over
whether money from Britain's aid budget should be sent Malaysia.
Sir Timothy Lankester, then permanent secretary at the Overseas Development
Administration, told Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, that he would
not authorise spending on Pergau.
Mr Hurd issued a ministerial direction, overruling Sir Timothy's advice and
in effect forcing him to sign the cheques for the deal.
</TEXT>
