<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Revived Major targets spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major last night sought to capitalise on the recent upturn in his
fortunes within the Tory party with the promise of a renewed squeeze on
public spending to pave the way for income tax cuts.
In a confident end-of-term address to Tory MPs, the prime minister pledged
to put 'clear water' between the Conservatives and Labour before the general
election due by mid 1997.
Confirming the rightwards tilt in his political strategy, Mr Major said the
government would begin preparations for its election manifesto as early as
this autumn. Policy committees would be established to reconnect the party's
priorities with the preoccupations of its grass-roots supporters.
His comments, ahead of a planned cabinet reshuffle within the next two
weeks, attracted strong applause from a packed audience of backbench MPs.
In spite of a sideswipe against the extreme Thatcherites who have suggested
that the party needs a period of opposition to restore its ideological
fervour, the general view on the Tory right was that Mr Major had heeded
warnings not to fight Labour for the political centre ground.
Erstwhile enemies on the Euro-sceptic right said the prime minister had
further diminished the prospect of an autumn leadership challenge.
Anticipating the election of Mr Tony Blair as Labour leader, Mr Major said
his aim would be to give clearer definition and distinction to the Tory
message. That meant a 'compact' legislative programme for the next session
of parliament in the autumn focusing on a number of key priorities.
Mr Major described Mr Blair as 'one of those politicians who likes climbing
up the ladder of opportunity but kicking it down for others'.
He gave no timetable for the implementation of tax cuts but MPs at the
meeting said he left the deliberate impression that some reduction would be
possible before the next election. The prime minister indicated that those
lower down the income scale would be the first beneficiaries of a reduction
in the tax burden.
Foreshadowing another cabinet battle over priorities in this autumn's
spending negotiations, Mr Major said that the Pounds 15bn which the
government had cut last November from spending plans over the next three
years was not enough. The cash targets set in the November Budget would be
further reduced.
Mr Major also said he would continue to press the case for a flexible rather
than centralised European Union.
He dismissed as 'futile' arguments over whether Britain should be in
Europe's fast or slow lanes insisting that 'people cannot be taken too far
or too fast in a direction they are instinctively loathe to go'. Instead
Britain would insist Europe took the 'right track'.
Joe Rogaly, Page 16
</TEXT>
