<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Ports sold off short, say MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was criticised by an all-party committee of MPs yesterday for
allowing the resale of a leading UK port to deprive a large part of its
workforce of the full value of their shareholding.
The port of Medway was acquired by its management and workforce in 1992 for
Pounds 29.7m and sold 18 months later to Mersey Docks for Pounds 103m.
The trust ports of Tees and Hartlepool, Clyde, Forth, Medway and the Port of
London were sold for Pounds 380m of which Pounds 169m went in the form of a
levy to the government.
In the period up to the second sale the Medway workforce was reduced from
688 to 260 in spite of an earlier promise from its management that it would
maintain the terms and conditions of the employees at the existing level.
More than 250 of the employees who lost their jobs were required to sell
back shares worth Pounds 35 for only Pounds 2.50. 'We are surprised that the
resale value of the shares was not covered in the sale agreement,' the
committee said.
It urged the government consider ways of inserting binding undertakings into
agreements reached for any future sales to ensure that bidders stood by
promises made to workers.
It also called for the government to consider introducing a clawback on
increases in the value of shares where the increase resulted from the
buyer's failure to meet undertakings given at the sale time.
The reduction in the size of the Medway workforce and the forced sale of
employees' shares made a significant difference to profitability.
The committee was also critical of the government for failing to obtain the
best price for the five ports. It said that it was 'particularly concerned'
at the price difference between the first and second sales of Medway. The
port fetched little more than three quarters of the lower benchmark
valuation when it was first sold to its workers but more than three times as
much 18 months later. This second sale led to the management and their
backers making a far greater profit than the Pounds 13m received by the
taxpayer on the initial privatisation.
The committee said it was concerned that in two of the five sales the price
reached was below the lower benchmark valuation which had been made. The
upper benchmark was achieved in only one of the sales.
Department of Transport: The First Sales of Trust Ports. HMSO Pounds 8.95.
</TEXT>
