<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Foreign Office taps reserves for peacekeeping bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Foreign Office is set to contribute Pounds 200m more than it budgeted
for to United Nations peacekeeping operations this year, forcing it to draw
on the government's Pounds 3.5bn contingency reserve.
Mr Alastair Goodlad, Foreign Office minister, said in a Commons written
answer that the Foreign Office diplomatic-wing cash limit on 'other external
relations' for 1994-95 would be almost doubled from Pounds 211.4m to Pounds
415.5m.
This was mainly to take account of contributions to UN peacekeeping
operations.
More than half the increase is attributable to the UN protection force in
the former Yugoslavia. But contributions to UN operations as far afield as
Haiti, Rwanda and Nagorno-Karabakh are also taken into account.
The increase will spark concern among Tory right-wingers anxious to see
public spending reduced in order to make room for early tax cuts.
Mr John Townend, chairman of the Tory backbench finance committee, said
yesterday that he did not see why British taxpayers should foot the bill.
'We are involved in peacekeeping on behalf of the UN because our armed
forces are arguably the most efficient in the world,' he said. 'Other
wealthy countries with no troops in the region - for example Germany and
Japan - should pay.'
Mr Townend has long argued that the government should make deep cuts in
Britain's foreign aid budget as part of a drive to rein in spend-ing.
Foreign Office spending on peacekeeping has risen rapidly in recent years,
multiplying seven-fold from Pounds 32m to Pounds 225m between 1990-91 and
1993-94.
The Foreign Office used this year's departmental report to comment on the
'significant increase' in international peacekeeping activities which has
been undertaken by the UN and other international bodies. It noted that such
operations 'cannot be planned for in advance'.
</TEXT>
