<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Ports sold off short, say MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government failed to obtain the best price for five ports sold to the
private sector in 1992, a cross-party committee of MPs found yesterday.
The sale agreements also failed to take sufficient account of the interests
of employees who were encouraged to buy shares in their companies, according
to a report by the Commons public accounts committee.
The trust ports of Tees and Hartlepool, Clyde, Forth, Medway and the Port of
London were sold for Pounds 380m of which Pounds 169m went in the form of a
levy to the government.
The committee said it was concerned that in two of the five sales the price
reached was below the lower benchmark valuation which had been made. The
upper benchmark was achieved in only one of the sales.
It was 'particularly concerned' that Medway was sold for Pounds 29.7m,
little more than three quarters of the lower benchmark, and then resold 18
months later for Pounds 103m to Mersey Docks. This second sale led to the
management and their backers making a far greater profit than the taxpayer
on privatisation.
There were also delays in collecting the government's share of these
disposals which cost the taxpayer Pounds 4.5m, the committee found. This
delay arose partly because of disputes with two of the ports about whether
certain expenses were deductible.
The committee urged the government to consider ways of inserting binding
undertakings into agreements reached for any future sales to ensure that
bidders stood by promises made to the workforce.
The Port of Medway reduced its workforce from 688 to 260 in spite of an
earlier statement from its management that it would maintain the terms and
conditions of the employees at the existing level.
Employees who lost their jobs were required to sell back shares worth Pounds
35 for only Pounds 2.50. 'We are surprised that the re-sale value of the
shares was not covered in the sale agreement,' the committee said.
It called for the government to consider introducing a clawback on increases
in the value of shares where the increase resulted from the buyer's failure
to meet undertakings given at the time of the sale.
The reduction in the Medway workforce and the forced sale of employees'
shares made a significant difference to profitability.
Department of Transport: The First Sales of Trust Ports. HMSO. Pounds 8.95.
</TEXT>
