<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Hurd tames plans for civil service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, has warned ministerial colleagues that
reform of the civil service must be accompanied by respect for its core
values.
As officials yesterday disclosed that he had prevented radical moves to
privatise services in the forthcoming Cabinet Office white paper, Mr Hurd
said ministers should accept the valuable service they receive from civil
servants.
He told the FDA top civil servants union this week: 'The Conservative
government should not regard the civil service either as some hidden enemy,
or as a body of partisan supporters.'
He said loyalty could only work in both directions. Just as the civil
service would have to accept reform of its working practices, so ministers
would have to accept that the civil service remained an essential element of
Britain's constitution.
Ms Elizabeth Symons, the FDA general secretary, yesterday said: 'Senior
civil servants were so relieved to hear a minister praising the civil
service instead of attacking it.'
The white paper is expected to propose an end to centralised pay bargaining
in Whitehall but to reject some of the more radical moves to privatise
services supported by Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister.
Mr Hurd made it clear that he wanted to reaffirm the civil service's values
of integrity, impartiality and selection and promotion on merit.
</TEXT>
