<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Redwood to shake up rural Welsh quango
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Welsh quango which was attacked by MPs is to be revamped, with some of its
functions transferred to local authorities.
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, told the Commons yesterday that the
Development Board for Rural Wales, which the Commons public accounts
committee censured in May, would retain its core functions. But it would
have to liaise more closely with the Welsh Development Agency, and Mr David
Rowe-Beddoe, chairman of the WDA, would take over as chairman of both
agencies.
The development board, based in Newtown, Powys, was set up nearly 20 years
ago to stem depopulation of rural Wales by promoting economic and social
development. It has a staff of 120 and a budget of Pounds 26.8m, including a
Welsh Office grant of nearly Pounds 17m.
Mr Redwood said in March that he was reviewing its future. This led to
speculation it would be subsumed into the WDA, which in turn triggered a
campaign by business and political leaders in Wales for its retention.
The Welsh secretary acknowledged yesterday that there was 'considerable
support' for the development board's work in property development and
business services. These functions would remain with it. To increase local
accountability, two additional councillors would be appointed to the board.
Councils will take over the development board's responsibility for a variety
of grant schemes from next year, Mr Redwood said. Its tourism activities
would transfer to the Wales Tourist Board and the WDA would take 'a strong
lead' in promoting inward investment.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe said last night: 'There will certainly be no takeover of the
DBRW by the WDA.'
The Commons public accounts committee heavily criticised the development
board in May and Mr Glyn Davies, its chairman for the seven years, resigned.
The committee's report said it had failed to comply with housing acts by
operating two sets of rules for housing allocation - one set of which was
unpublished. Under the undisclosed rules, the housing officer and his
ex-wife were given homes they were not qualified for under the public rules.
There was also criticism of a car-leasing scheme.
Ivor Owen writes: Mr Redwood said he had no plans for primary legislation to
deal with what Mr Rhodri Morgan, a Labour spokesman on Wales, described as
the 'legal difficulties' faced by the development board.
The minister said he had decided to review the board's future long before
any doubts arose because he wished to develop policy in a new direction.
</TEXT>
