<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / W Midlands businesses report faltering outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Economic recovery in the west Midlands has reached a plateau and confidence
about immediate prospects for corporate profitability has faltered,
according to a survey of business performance carried out by chambers of
commerce.
But the proportion of companies recruiting more staff has increased and, for
the services sector, there have been increasing difficulties in finding
skilled manual labour.
The West Midlands Regional Group of Chambers of Commerce quarterly survey,
published today, shows that the rise in domestic orders experienced in the
first quarter of the year was not repeated in the second.
In June, 42 per cent of the 455 manufacturing companies covered in the
survey reported home orders higher than three months before. But in March 46
per cent of companies reported fatter order books, up from 37 per cent in
December 1993.
In the services sector, the same pattern emerged. Of the 187 companies
taking part in the survey, 47 per cent reported increased orders in June
against 57 per cent in March and 38 per cent in December.
But there is a disparity of performance in overseas markets. The proportion
of manufacturing companies reporting higher export orders rose to 36 per
cent from 34 per cent but the proportion of service companies was down from
40 per cent to 26 per cent.
The survey suggests that companies are far more cautious about the immediate
future than cabinet ministers. In June, 44 per cent of manufacturing
companies and 46 per cent of service companies were expecting higher profits
over the next year, but in March the proportions were, respectively 47 per
cent and 50 per cent. Further evidence that tax rises and the fear of higher
mortgage rates have slowed down the recovery in the housing market emerged
yesterday with the publication of a national survey of estate agents.
The survey by the National Association of Estate Agents showed that 43 per
cent of its members had reported less business during June, compared with 22
per cent reporting more business.
</TEXT>
