<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Demand for the government's loan guarantee scheme increased sharply in the
first quarter of the year, Lord Strathclyde, small companies minister, said
yesterday. This was one of a number of factors demonstrating renewed health
of the smaller-company sector,
The minister was launching the Department of Trade and Industry's first
annual review of the state of small companies in Britain.
Applications for loan guarantees rose in the first quarter to 500 a month
from 300 a month in the same quarter last year. The scheme is designed to
support companies that either lack security or sufficient track record to
raise bank finance. However, the failure rate for companies supported by the
scheme remains high.
