<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Turkish privatisation setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey's privatisation programme suffered another setback with the
constitutional court ruling late yesterday to cancel the recently passed
enabling legislation which would have allowed the government to sell
companies without having to seek parliamentary approval. The move will delay
the programme at a time when Mrs Tansu Ciller, the prime minister, is trying
to speed up the sale of state assets to bolster the balance of payments and
avoid a debt rescheduling. The court decision means that separate
legislation will have to be presented to parliament for debate in the case
of the sale of every state company. 'Practically speaking, it means the
policy is doomed,' said the deputy leading the appeal to the constitutional
court to have the law annulled. Turkey was aiming to sell Dollars 2.5bn
worth of assets this year, including companies in the oil refining and
distribution sectors, the state airline, steel concern and the state
telecommunications.
</TEXT>
