<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Economic Watch: Turkish current account boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey's current account showed a surplus of Dollars 342m (Pounds 225m) in
April, the first sign of the effect of government austerity measures. The
current account deficit in the first quarter was reduced to Dollars 778m
compared with Dollars 1.8bn in 1993. The figures appear to support
government forecasts that the current account will be close to balanced this
year, against a record deficit of Dollars 6.3bn in 1993, following the sharp
contraction in domestic demand and the lira's devaluation. Official reserves
fell Dollars 3bn in the first quarter, as the central bank sought
unsuccessfully to prop up the lira. There was also a Dollars 1.4bn
short-term capital outflow in the period, compared with an inflow of Dollars
1.3bn in 1993, as banks closed their foreign exchange positions. Tourism
revenues were steady at Dollars 690m. Debt servicing in the first quarter -
principal and interest - rose to Dollars 2.4bn, against Dollars 1.3bn in
1993, reflecting increased foreign borrowings last year.
Orders for west German builders were up 3.8 per cent in April from a year
earlier and rose 6.2 per cent in the first four months of 1994. New housing
orders were up 18 per cent in April and 27 per cent in the first four months
of 1994.
German crude steel output rose 8.4 per cent to 20.16m tonnes in the first
half this year from a year ago.
Poland had a current account deficit of Dollars 30m in May after a surplus
of Dollars 45m in the previous month.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TRZ  Turkey, Middle East.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
    PLZ  Poland, East Europe.
</CN>
