<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Railtrack closer to deal with union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The signalling workers' dispute that has disrupted Britain's rail network
over the past four weeks is much closer to a settlement than either
Railtrack or the RMT transport union are prepared to admit in public.
Railtrack believes the glare of publicity has diverted attention from the
attractive details of its three-part productivity package which it presented
to union negotiators at the conciliation service Acas on June 27.
The package would give the signal staff on average an extra Pounds 335 in
their pay packets between now and the end of September. This would take the
form of a 6 per cent unconsolidated rise in basic rates from July 1 and an
immediate Pounds 200 lump sum for every signal worker in return for agreeing
to be paid by credit transfer.
In addition, all staff would get a 2.5 per cent annual pay rise, payable at
once.
Railtrack has calculated that the first two parts of its self-financing
efficiency package are worth more than the extra Pounds 240 signal staff
would have received by October 1 if the company had agreed to a 5.7 per cent
interim pay rise. Such an offer, designed to restore signalling staff
differentials, was discussed with the RMT in early June before the one-day
strikes began.
The company hopes that by the end of September a full restructuring deal can
be negotiated with the union that will provide most signalling staff with
rises in their basic rates of 13 to 26 per cent.
Railtrack is spelling out clearly on its telephone hotline what the total
package would be worth to each signalman. So far the staff have lost around
Pounds 260 each in pay for going on strike.
Both the company and the union accept the need for a restructuring deal and
agree on the need for a joint working party to hammer out final details by
October 1 to enable signal staff to benefit from improved pension
arrangements. After that date the pension fund will be split up and the
improvements will not be possible.
Railtrack believes it has now shaped a highly attractive package for staff
and that there is enough common ground to resolve the conflict.
Relief signalling staff have told Railtrack, however, that they need more
detail on the way they are to be compensated for the cut in earnings they
will suffer as a result of the proposed package. The company is keen to
stress that the details of the self-financing deal are open to negotiation
but not the principles behind it.
Yesterday, Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, asked Railtrack to provide
what he called 'vital information' on the package. He wants detailed figures
on the effect of the savings Railtrack would achieve over the next 15 years
and specific earnings and weekly hours required by each grade.
Mr Bob Horton, Railtrack's chairman, said yesterday after hour-long talks
with Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, that he hoped there could be a
settlement of the signalling staff dispute 'before too long'.
Although he added that his meeting at the transport department was
'routine', Mr Horton said there had been, 'among other items', a discussion
of the conflict that has closed down most of the railway network for the
past four Wednesdays.
Yesterday it was revealed in a written Commons answer that part-time board
members receive a Pounds 500 payment for each board meeting they attend in
addition to their annual Pounds 10,000 salary.
</TEXT>
