<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 94 / Lords warn on job references: Managers encouraged to watch
their words in assessment of staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, LISA WOOD and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The legal scales tipped in favour of job hunters yesterday when the House of
Lords ruled that employers have a duty to take reasonable care when writing
references about former staff members.
The case opens the possibility of court actions against companies on the
grounds that they have been negligent in assessing the conduct and behaviour
of employees, so damaging their chances of gaining work with other
organisations.
Although legal experts and companies were divided about the practical impact
of the Law Lords' ruling, the case seems certain to lead to managers
thinking more deeply about the implications of the thousands of references
written every day.
One effect, however, could be to encourage the practice of giving
confidential references over the telephone, making it virtually impossible
for disgruntled employees to bring legal cases.
In yesterday's opinion, the Law Lords ruled, by a majority of four to one,
that Guardian Assurance, a subsidiary of the Guardian Royal Exchange
investment group, had not taken sufficient care when writing a reference on
Mr Graham Spring, a former insurance salesman.
The reference stated that Mr Spring had 'little or no integrity and could
not be regarded as honest'. Mr Spring claimed this was untrue and that the
reference meant he could not get another insurance job.
Mr Tony Morgan, director of the Industrial Society, a body promoting good
employment practice, said: 'A reference can affect the rest of somebody's
life, so integrity is vital. This ruling will focus employers on good
practice, which is to provide references which are fair and authentic, not
opinionated and anecdotal.'
Mr Witold Pawlak, Mr Spring's barrister, said the decision was of 'immense
importance' and 'fills a gap in the law'.
Mr Fraser Younson, vice-president of the Employment Lawyers Association,
said employers already had to be circumspect in giving references because
they owed a duty of care to the recipient company. The Law Lords had now
extended that duty to employees. The effect could be that employers adopt a
more tentative approach to references.
The judgment's most immediate impact is likely to be in the insurance
industry, which faces legal action by hundreds of former sales agents who
have lost their jobs in the past four years.
Other industries which have suffered in recent years from allegations about
damaging references include accountancy, medicine and the legal profession.
A practical difficulty in future cases, however, may be that it is often
difficult for an employee to see his or her reference, which is normally
given confidentially to potential employers.
In Mr Spring's case, it took five court legal hearings before a High Court
judge ordered GRE to hand over the reference. GRE said about Mr Spring's
reference: 'It is fair to say it should have been crafted in a different
way.'
The legal outcome for Mr Spring is still hazy since his case has to return
to the Court of Appeal for more judgments which may settle his claim for
damages, thought to amount to tens of thousands of pounds.
</TEXT>
