<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / Building societies given chance to widen services: Boards to
be more accountable to members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Building societies will be able to offer a wider range of services but will
also have to be more accountable to their members, under government plans
released yesterday.
Setting out the plans, which affect business loans and societies' ownership
of insurance companies, Mr Anthony Nelson, Treasury economic secretary, made
it clear that the government did not intend to relax the stringent statutory
controls which have made societies so difficult for other institutions to
take over.
'We don't want to be spoil-sports but I don't want a duckshoot of the
building societies,' he said. He added, however, that he wanted to see the
benefits of mutual ownership being passed more directly to society members,
perhaps through dividends.
A second stage to the Treasury's review of societies' legislation will
examine how to promote change in the sector, whether societies' powers could
be more systematically streamlined, and how society directors could be more
effectively held to account by members.
Yesterday's announcement includes a requirement for societies' boards to
inform their members at the next general meeting of any non-confidential
takeover offers from organisations other than societies.
This falls short of the call from some senior bankers for an end to the
power of boards to block an offer from another institution by refusing to
put it to society members for a decision.
The government's plans will also allow societies to broaden the range of
business lending they can carry out by enabling them to set up subsidiaries
to make loans which are not secured on land.
Putting this in the context of the Treasury's separate inquiry into the
funding of industry, Mr Nelson said this would provide a welcome new source
of funds for business. It would also, he added, 'introduce a new element of
competition into an area traditionally dominated by a small number of high
street banks'.
Societies will be able to wholly own general insurance companies offering a
limited range of cover related to housing - buildings and contents insurance
and mortgage payment protection. At present, there is a limit of 15 per cent
on a society's stake in a general insurance company.
As widely expected, the ceiling on the proportion of funds that societies
can raise on the wholesale money markets is to rise, from 40 per cent to 50
per cent.
The initiatives, which will begin to come into effect over the coming
months, mark the end of the first stage of the Treasury review.
In the second stage, a consultation paper will be published, probably in
September. The exercise is intended to be completed by the end of this year.
Alongside the emphasis on accountability, which could lead to reserving some
board places for members' representatives, it will also look at specific
changes to the legislation, including the pay-outs that can be made to
members of societies which come together in a traditional merger.
</TEXT>
