<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / FT Exporter (18): UK operators look to the east - The
developing country markets are producing a growing supply of big business
deals / Contract awards / Diary, FT Exporter reviews recent export contracts
and developments in UK support for its exporters and provides a calendar of
upcoming international trade fairs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROD MCNEIL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK exporters are continuing to make their mark in hotly-contested developing
country markets. Significant deals have recently been won in China, Vietnam
and Africa.
Michael Heseltine, President of the Board of Trade, underscores the strength
of opportunity for UK exporters in China. 'The Chinese economy is growing by
leaps and bounds. By the end of this century, it will be eight times bigger
than it was at the start of the '80s. This matches the best performance of
Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.'
He adds: 'Our exports to China were up by nearly 40 per cent in the first
four months of this year compared with last year's performance. But there is
much more out there to be won - by Britain's small and medium-sized
companies as well as the big players.'
Indicative of recent UK export wins in the face of stiff international
competition is Taylor Woodrow International's Pounds 60m management contract
for the re-development of Kowloon station in Hong Kong in a market which the
company sees as a gateway into China - in a competitive bid involving six
other international contractors. Bruce Russell, managing director of Taylor
Woodrow International, says: 'We were competing on the strength of our
management skills and know-how, not price.'
Mr Russell describes the deal as a low-risk project representing part of the
company's strategy of breaking into the Hong Kong market. 'We have always
regarded Hong Kong as an opportunity area and a stepping stone into China,'
he says.
Two export strategies are being exploited. 'First, to enter as a
construction adviser or design and construction partner on the back of
foreign inward investments, principally in light industrial and commercial
development projects,' Mr Russell says. 'Second, self-developed and financed
BOOT (build-own-operate-transfer) projects relating to infrastructure
developments in power, water and transportation'.
Taylor Woodrow aims to conclude agreements on several additional Chinese
projects in the near future. 'The Chinese authorities are proving very
receptive to foreign participation. We are on a fast-track learning curve,
and so are they,' says Mr Russell.
Other notable successes to China in recent months include:
CAD Centre, the Cambridge-based supplier of computer-aided design systems
for the process plant and power industries, won orders worth Dollars 250,000
for the sale of process plant design software to four customers in the oil
and chemical sectors. 'We regard China and Asia as an area of great
opportunity for our products,' says managing director Bob Bishop.
APV received contracts for the supply of processing equipment to China's
manufacturing sector, including a Pounds 6m order for dry yeast processing
equipment for a large liquor producer.
Trafalgar House subsidiary Cemetics International won a Dollars 6m contract
to supply equipment and field advisory services to the Shanyang Smelter
sulphuric acid plant in Liaoning province. Cemetics has won 17 contracts to
supply equipment to sulphuric acid plants in China since the mid-1980s.
Others have registered their first successes in China. Birwelco, the
Halesowen-based specialist engineering contractor to the water, process and
waste industries, won - for a British company - a key engineering contract
in the water treatment field in China.
Working in collaboration with Yorkshire Water, which itself won a Dollars
5.5m plant and equipment supply contract, Birwelco will be involved in the
design and construction of a rapid gravity filtration plant for the Daqing
oilfield in Heilongjiang province in north-west China. The contract, signed
with the China National Technical Import Corporation in May, is part of a
Dollars 150m oilfield development project.
'China represents a completely new market for us,' says Brian Cartwright of
Birwelco. 'We secured the contract against fierce international competition
because we had the best and most economical tender. We are looking at other
market areas including Thailand and Taiwan, where there are enormous
opportunities'.
The company is working on a feasibility project for a waste-powered energy
plant in Taiwan in association with local state authorities and private
enterprise.
Elsewhere, Vietnam is unfolding as a rewarding export target. Serck Baker,
the process engineering subsidiary of Meggitt, specialising in the design
and supply of equipment to the oil and gas sector, won its second export
contract to Vietnam in June, just weeks after the delivery of its first
Vietnamese export contract.
In conjunction with Sembawang of Singapore, Serck Baker will design, project
manage, engineer and procure oil and gas production equipment for a major
Vietnamese energy production project. The multi-million dollar deal
represents Serck Baker's largest-ever export project.
'The Far East market has always been an important market for us, and
continues to be,' says Jim Dawson, director of Meggitt Energy Division. 'And
with the decline in North Sea development, this market becomes a great deal
more significant.'
Smaller companies are also demonstrating the advantages of market
diversification. Carbolite, producer of laboratory furnaces, has notched up
successes in Turkey, China and, more recently South Africa and India, with
exports accounting for more than two-thirds of its Pounds 7m annual
turnover. As part of a recent Pounds 350,000 export contract, the company
will supply a continuous hardening and tempering line for an Indian
manufacturer of cutting strip.
Norman Short, marketing director, explains: 'We look strategically at all
markets where we believe export demand is going to come in the next five
years. We are looking at Vietnam and are currently negotiating the
appointment of a locally-based and well-equipped distributor.'
Meanwhile, the defence sector, galvanised by shrinking defence budgets in
maturing markets, continues to seek new ventures in the developing world. In
late June, Radio Racal won a Pounds 7.5m contract for its Tacnet tactical
area communications network and field telephone system from a major African
customer, for use by the country's armed forces.
The deal, the result of two years' negotiations, involved competitive
demonstrations alongside French and Israeli manufacturers' equipment. 'This
particular deal was significant in that it represented a breakthrough in
ousting an incumbent competitor - a French radio company - who had been
supplying the customer for several years' says Adrian Day, managing director
of Racal Radio Group. 'They fought us hard, but our product and
cost-effectiveness proved superior.'
Earlier in June, the company won a Pounds 25m contract to supply the
Republic of Korea's navy with a new command control console. It has also
booked record export volumes into Latin America. 'This year our export order
intake is running at twice or three times the level seen over the past five
years,' says Mr Day.
</TEXT>
