<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / FT Exporter (16): Competition for orders is tough - The
World Bank and other agencies are a vital source of finance for projects in
developing countries, writes Alan Spence / Multilateral lending agencies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN SPENCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Project financing by the World Bank, regional institutions such as the Asian
Development Bank (ADB), the EU and other multilateral agencies is big
business. International companies secured project contracts financed by the
World Bank worth Dollars 9,098m in 1992 alone. In heavily indebted
developing countries and cash-strapped regions, such as eastern Europe, the
intervention of multilateral international financial institutions (IFIs) is
often essential if a project is to go ahead.
Competition for orders can be severe. It is not unusual to find dozens of
companies pre-qualifying for the more attractive orders. The EU's Tacis
programme for the former Soviet Union received more than 200 requests to
pre-qualify for one military conversion contract.
Project cycles may be long and even having the guarantee of World Bank or EU
financing does not ensure that the contract will be trouble free. But the
rewards may be substantial. World Bank-financed orders totalling Dollars
607m went to UK exporters in 1992 and in 1993 the figure rose to Dollars
727m.
The World Bank says it finances more than 200 projects every year, leading
to the award of some 30,000 contracts. About 70 per cent of these are for
equipment and other capital goods. Contracts for dams, power networks and
other big ticket contracts make headlines, but a high proportion of
multilateral financing backs much smaller orders. According to the World
Bank typical contracts secured in early 1994 by UK companies were ASC, which
has a Dollars 12.95m order for grain handling equipment for China, and
Telspec, whose Dollars 5.99m contract is to supply loop carrier equipment to
the Slovak Republic.
In regions such as Africa, accessing multilateral-funded contracts is often
the only way to do business. 'Most of our sub-Saharan business is based on
aid,' a UK exporter says. His company employs specialist teams to monitor
aid-related business opportunities across the globe. 'Such is the range of
aid-related lending that many companies either focus on just one or several
related countries where they can build up specialist knowledge.
For SMEs and even multinationals, such approaches may not prove practical.
Support from government to help identify opportunities is available to most
exporters. The UK's Department of Trade &amp; Industry (DTI), for example,
provides specialist advice through its World Aid Section (WAS), which
receives some 20,000 telephone enquiries and 3,000 company visits annually.
The WAS helps to target markets and sectors for UK exporters unsure of what
is on offer. It holds the details of more than 5,000 projects on its files,
published through the DTI's Export Intelligence Service.
For a company seeking to tap multilateral financing for the first time, the
initial priority is to learn more about the multilateral's operations and
business practices.
Bidding for multilateral finance work can be a protracted process. One
exporter, who has secured a Dollars 1.6m supply deal in south-east Asia
financed by the ADB, sums up a wider view: while he is pleased with the
business, there are frustrations. 'It takes a long time for the bureaucratic
wheels to turn,' he says.
Local contacts are essential. Having identified that international financing
is available for a project - often through an advance tender notice
published by the World Bank, ADB or other agency in their own or commercial
publications - a company should seek out the relevant implementing agency.
WAS officials suggest providing the buyer with product information and
establishing contact with officials.
The World Bank's international competitive bidding (ICB) process is designed
to allow local and international companies equal opportunities to bid. ICB
sets out standard rules for bidding. These include regulations stipulating
that documents must be written in English, Spanish or French.
A margin of preference must be given to local firms. Manufactured goods with
a minimum of 20 per cent of domestic content are afforded a margin of
preference equal to the applicable customs and import tariff, or 15 per cent
of the cost, insurance and freight price of the imported goods by the
competitor.
Contracts must be awarded to the lowest evaluated bid, although this may not
be the cheapest.
WAS officials say it is crucial that firms price their bids competitively,
comply precisely with all contractual specifications and pay special
attention to security and deadline arrangements. This can prove expensive.
ICB tenders issued by the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
(EBRD) specify security to accompany the bid of 'not less than 2 per cent of
the total bid amount in any freely convertible currency'.
Increasing flows of financing from the World Bank, EBRD, the EU's Phare and
Tacis technical assistance programmes means that eastern Europe is a
substantial area for aid-related growth. This is critical in countries where
mobilising other forms of export financing can prove highly problematic.
A pointer to the future is the EBRD's policy of signing agreements with
bilateral agencies and banks to back export-related projects. To assist
private sector buyers, the London-based bank has recently signed agreements
with the Export-Import Bank of Japan, Mexico's Banco Nacional de Comercio
Exterior (Bancomext) and the Austrian government.
These accords give EBRD backing to export credits, insurance and guarantees
and investment-related financing - helping banks and export credit agencies
to increase their funding capacity in difficult markets.
The EBRD has also established a Dollars 10m trade facility for Macedonia,
guaranteeing designated correspondent banks of the Skopje-based Komercijalna
Banka against non-payment of unconfirmed letters of credit.
The facility is intended to increase commercial trade finance flows to a
'difficult market'. It marks the recognition that in many parts of the world
IFI support is essential if contracts of all sizes are to be signed - and
that the development finance institutions and their clients can no longer
live by prestige projects alone.
Additional research by Kevin Godier
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    LUZ  Luxembourg, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6111 Federal and Federally-Sponsored Credit Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
