<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / FT Exporter (8): Sector yet to recover from the crisis - The
industry, which suffered more than most from the effects of recession, has
still a long way to go in rebuilding its competitiveness in export markets
/ German machine tools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The German machine tool industry has long prided itself on its powerful
presence in export markets, claiming a 27 per cent share of world trade.
Even during the now-fading recession, it boasted that it was gaining share
at the expense of the Japanese who were labouring under a high yen and
relatively high dependence on their weak domestic market.
But the gains came at the cost of evaporating profits and a slump in
production which dragged output last year to half its record 1989 level.
The machine tool business was the first part of the German engineering
industry to plunge into recession. The blows rained hard and fast, starting
in 1990. Much of the rest of the sector was enjoying the fruits of the
German unification boom, shipping cars, consumer durables and building
machinery equipment. But east German demand for machine tools failed to
materialise as the region's industry crumbled.
Meanwhile, recession and political and economic turmoil struck the sector's
main export markets elsewhere in Europe. German machine tool makers have
traditionally exported a good 60 per cent of their output, maintaining a 20
per cent share of world markets. Some 70 per cent of all foreign sales go
elsewhere in Europe (17 per cent to the former east bloc), and only 10 per
cent each to the US and south-east Asia.
This dependence on Europe was arguably the worst structural problem exposed
by the economic turmoil. The VWD manufacturers association pointed out last
year that the industry was most strongly established in the slowest-growing
markets. Its products were too expensive and failed to meet market needs.
Without counter-measures, it said, German volume output would fall to 50 per
cent of that in Japan by the end of the decade.
Much management energy has been expended on regaining cost-competitiveness.
The main methods have been reductions in staff and vertical integration.
Schutte, a typical medium-sized private company, for example, has halved its
workforce to about 660. Pittler, one of the bigger concerns, claims its new
policy of buying certain components from low-cost east European suppliers,
has reduced overall materials costs by 20 per cent.
Inventive, customer-specific technologies and software - increasingly
developed in partnership with the end-user - have helped German
manufacturers compensate partially for the losses in the market for
mass-produced standard machines which is falling increasingly under Asian
control.
But convincing ways have yet to be found for the industry to establish
itself firmly in fast-growing Asian markets. Some observers believe the
industry should accept that opportunities are limited and concentrate on
specialist niches and the 'home' European market.
They argue that 'local' suppliers in Asia are already firmly settled, and
that the risks and the costs of establishing plant or even distribution and
service networks are too high for most German companies in the sector. Many
are small or medium-sized, highly-specialised enterprises with only modest
volumes. They are often privately-owned, and their finances have been
weakened by the recent crisis.
Suggestions that they may gain critical mass through merger or takeover have
been met with a resistance peculiar to Germany's fiercely independent
entrepreneurial Mittelstand. Indeed, the board of the only significant
recent merger - between Deckel and Maho - filed for protection from their
creditors within a year of the deal's conclusion.
However, not everything has been lost. The joint distribution and service
network between Deckel and Maho, which was seen as one of the main sources
of synergies, has been taken over by Gildemeister, which is in turn
interested in building a reciprocal sales/service relationship with
Cincinnati Milacron of the US.
Even wider synergies are apparently being sought within a holding group,
Autania, which last year came under the control of the publicly-owned
WestDeutsche Landesbank. Autania, which claims to be Europe's biggest
machine tools 'group', has stakes in about 20 different companies. It was
built up by the Rothenberger family as an investment vehicle, but WestLB has
grander plans. On taking control, the bank announced the individual stakes
were to be increased, and Autania was to be transformed into a 'world market
alliance'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
