<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / FT Exporter (6): The move towards global purchasing - Kevin
Done looks at the way Ford's CDW-27 project is showing how many of the
company's planned reforms can be implemented / Global sourcing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This autumn Ford, the world's second largest carmaker is launching the US
versions of its so-called CDW-27 world car programme, a Dollars 6bn project
that has helped to lay the foundations for one of the most radical
organisational shake-ups in the US car maker's 91-year history.
The programme has already spawned the Ford Mondeo large family car, which
was launched in Europe in spring last year, and Ford is preparing to put the
sister cars, the Ford Contour and the Mercury Mystique, on sale in north
America.
The CDW-27 project has convinced the company that it is possible to design,
develop and engineer a car in one region - in this case Europe  - for
manufacture in at least two regions - north America and Europe - for sale
around the globe. It has given Ford the confidence to develop a bold
strategy for restructuring its entire automotive operations - including the
way that it deals with its components suppliers around the world.
It is merging its European and north American operations into a single
operating unit, Ford Automotive Operations, with effect from next January.
It is setting up five so-called global vehicle centres, one in Europe and
four in the US, to break down the group's regional barriers. Each centre
will have worldwide responsibility for the design, development and
engineering of particular vehicle ranges.
The CDW-27 project, Ford's first successful world car programme, has
prepared the way for the reorganisation and brought Ford for the first time
to the global purchasing of components and systems.
Ford maintains that this will provide 'economies of scale, world-class
supplier productivity and cost levels, improved quality, faster time to
market, better product innovation and enhanced supplier design involvement
and support.' It will also mean that it will be able to choose the best
products to be offered worldwide in any particular category.
The CDW-27 project is showing how many of the planned reforms can be
implemented. Versions of the Mondeo/Contour/Mystique will be assembled at
Ford plants at Genk, Belgium, at Kansas City in the US and at Cuautitlan,
Mexico. For the Mondeo programme alone Ford is spending Dollars 2.5bn a year
on components bought from outside suppliers.
According to Albert Caspers, Ford's new chairman for Europe, global
purchasing means that the share taken by north American suppliers has jumped
to 15 per cent for the European-built Mondeo compared with a share of only
1-2 per cent in Ford of Europe's traditional car programmes. 'We have also
brought many European suppliers to north America and some have made joint
ventures in the US,' he says. 'The philosophy was to develop a part only
once from one supplier for the world. This is the first project where we
have done this.'
Ford estimates that about Dollars 140m worth of components will be exported
annually to north America from Europe with about Dollars 260m worth of
components coming from north America to Europe as part of the Mondeo
programme.
The development of an integrated, global supply base has resulted in a
drastic reduction in the number of suppliers. The current US-built Ford
Tempo/Mercury Topaz range has more than 700 suppliers - all in North America
 -whereas the successor Ford Contour/Mercury Mystique models will have only
227 suppliers, drawn from around the world.
Kerry Caliman, CDW-27 project manager for purchasing for Ford's north
American automotive operations, says: 'the more business you can source
globally, using the same supplier for the same part for both North America
and Europe, the more you'll benefit from economies of scale and focused
quality control efforts'.
</TEXT>
