<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 94 / FT Exporter (5): Focus of trade constraints shifts - While
the demise of Comecon has led to an easing of controls, Alan Spence finds
that they have not disappeared altogether / High tech exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN SPENCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sale of high technology equipment to sensitive destinations has become
easier since the collapse of communism, but strict controls remain. The
Paris-based organisation Co-com - the co-ordinating committee on
multilateral export controls - went into voluntary retirement on March 30
this year after 47 years of curbing western military and high technology
exports to communist countries.
Members, comprising all the NATO allies except for Iceland, and including
Australia and Japan, will retain the current slate of banned items, although
enforcement will rely on national discretion.
The political and economic liberalisation within former Comecon countries
has reduced the western governments' need to control the sale to the region
of 'dual-use' technology - goods capable of, but not specially designed for,
military purposes.
But the collapse of communism in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union
does not mean that all restraints have disappeared. The focus of residual
controls has shifted to developing countries, especially, for example, North
Korea and Iran.
Reductions in trade constraints are reflected in the diminishing volumes of
export licences issued by the UK's Export Control Organisation (ECO), a unit
within the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI). About 21,000 licences
were approved by ECO in 1993, compared to about 100,000 in 1988. And the ECO
estimates provisioning of about 18,000-19,000 licences for 1994.
Cocom's final year was marked by the easing of restrictions, especially for
exporters of telecommunications equipment, computers and precision machine
tools. UK computer manufacturer ICL reports Pounds 60m worth of business in
eastern Europe for 1993, a figure 'substantially up from the previous year',
says a company spokesperson.
Cocom began to reduce a long list of proscribed items in 1990, while also
removing fast-reforming countries such as Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia
from sensitive destination categories.
On the day of Cocom's demise, the US Commerce Department removed licensing
requirements on almost all low level telecommunications equipment and
computers to every ex-communist nation except North Korea.
Constraints on UK exporters were further relaxed in May with an amendment to
the 1992 Export of Goods (Control) Order (EGCO). 'I expect a one-third
reduction in the number of licence applications for industrial goods alone,'
said Richard Needham, Britain's trade minister in response to the amendment.
ECO annual licensing for industrial 'dual-use' exports has fallen from about
60,000 in the late 1980s to below 10,000 at present. Exports of weapons of
mass destruction (WMDs) and associated components are still covered by three
principal non-proliferation controls: the 1968 Nuclear non-Proliferation
Treaty; the 1987 Missile Technology Control Regime; and the Australia Group,
which deals with chemical and biological warfare weaponry and components.
Under UK legislation passed in 1939 and amended in 1990, the legal onus lies
with the exporter to apply for a licence, when selling military equipment
and sophisticated dual-use technology overseas. Few cases are refused in
practice. Last year 300 applications were turned down. Successful UK
applications for military export licences average 12,000 per year, although
the May amendments to EGCO have increased restraints upon sales of armoured
vehicles, military components. digital controllers and testing equipment.
The growth area in control is developing countries where 41 destinations are
now subject to special licensing procedures.
Sanctions agreed by the UN Security Council include arms embargoes to
Somalia and Liberia, and complete embargoes upon trade with Iraq, Haiti and
Serbia-Montenegro. Certain goods are additionally prohibited from Libya and
Angola.
UK compliance procedures were upgraded in 1990 after difficulties with
Libyan exports. An 'end-use', or 'catch-all' control was introduced, forcing
would-be exporters to make reasonable enquiries to allay any suspicions
regarding use or destination.
This has been consolidated through the launch in March of the Export
Training Initiative - a package of materials for companies to promote
organisational awareness - and the publication of a Code of Practice for
Enforcement.
More than 200 annual compliance visits are made by ECO to UK companies to
reinforce the licensing process. These are mainly to companies with Open
Individual Export Licences which cover individual exporters for regular
shipments over two and three years to specified destinations.
Further information is available from DTI's Export Control Organisation
Enquiry Unit. Tel: +44 (0) 71 215 8079. Fax: +44 (0) 71 215 8564
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
